The paper deals with deep feature spaces and their ability to encode complex transformations of input data. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a method to construct a deep feature space with explicitly disentangled representations of known transformations, which involves the use of an encoder-decoder network with a custom feature transform layer. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the advantages of explicit disentangling for classification tasks, which suggests that it may belong to the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the nonlinear interactions between different factors, which suggests that it may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
